For top of the funnel content search is obviously the main channel (sometimes for medium funnel too) but for bottom funnel search is not effective as content pieces are not keyword based (although SEO optimized). Paid social? Email? anything else?

p.s. The course was super helpful

text:
Most people would probably say email, but it's definitely industry dependent. Some products/services have bottom-of-funnel terms with search volume.

For example, the CEO of Lufthansa isn't googling "best airplane maker," but a consumer may very well be googling "google tag manager course"—and buy yours on the spot.

Distribution channels are editorial flexibility. Search gives you access to a new audience; email lets you publish keyword-agnostic content.

And so on.

text:
Hi guys,

This might not be quite the slack group for this but its kind of content relevant.

I'm trying to solve a massive internal linking problem with our site content.  We have about 1500 pieces of content and 100 hubs living across 50 major product categories.  They're all linked terribly.

Ive done some small internal linking projects for 20-50 page projects but never anything on this scale.  Any suggestions what would be the simplest and most effective way to tackle this?  My initial thought is to find some tool/script where I can load up the 1500 main keywords for each article, have it look at "<site:mywebsite.com>" search results and then scrape the next 10-15 most relevant articles on our site from Google SERPs as best articles to crosslink with.

I'm sure someone has put more thought into this and has done this more elegantly and effectively.  Any advice or suggestions?  Any tools that specifically deal with this?

text:
You can use an agency..but most really good speakers have a team/site set up. You can just email and ask how much they charge and usually someone they employ will get back to you. Securing is mostly about money and timing since digital removes the travel side of things. I will caution speaker prices have not gone down at all despite the virtual vs in-person aspects you think would impact it or lower it...

If sourcing/finding the speaker is tough, an agency could help (if they have people that specialize in that)--but I will say tapping into our employee and partner network (especially that of our executive’s) actually led us to a great keynote. (A podcaster intro’d us to an up and coming author who was awesome at our conference and on budget.) The other was someone I had seen had/speak in the past.

Best of luck <@U013KUXL8GL>!

We put together a customer committee for our conference and sourced recommendations, having an intro always helps!

Having senior members of your org reach out (draft comms & messaging for them) can help break the ice too. Ie, CEO -> CEO, VP -> VP.

Hope that helps, and good luck!
